    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Sender reputation</strong> is the trust score that ISPs like Gmail, Outlook, and Yahoo assign to your email-sending domain and IP address. It functions like a credit score for email: ISPs route high-reputation senders to inboxes and low-reputation senders to spam — or block them entirely. You can't buy a good score; you earn it through consistent, low-complaint sending over weeks and months.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Bounce rate limit</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Under 0.5%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Email Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Complaint threshold</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Below 0.1%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Email generates $36 for every $1 spent — but only if it gets delivered. Sender reputation is the gating factor. A single poorly managed campaign can take a thriving email channel from 95% inbox placement to 30% in days, and the rebuild takes months of disciplined sending.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is sender reputation?</h2>
        <p>Sender reputation is the score ISPs assign to the combination of your sending domain and IP address. Every email you send contributes to it. ISPs evaluate signals across hundreds of millions of messages to determine whether your sending patterns look like a trusted business or a spammer.</p>
        <p>Google Postmaster Tools rates domain reputation on a four-tier scale:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>High</strong> — consistent inbox placement, low complaints, good authentication</li>
          <li><strong>Medium</strong> — mostly inbox, some filtering on high-volume days</li>
          <li><strong>Low</strong> — significant filtering; many emails diverted to spam</li>
          <li><strong>Bad</strong> — bulk rejection or blocking; requires active recovery</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Sender reputation is distinct from your brand reputation. You can have excellent products and a terrible sender reputation if you've neglected list hygiene, authentication, or engagement.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">How ISPs see you</div>
          <p>Each ISP scores you independently. A High rating in Google Postmaster Tools does not mean Outlook's SNDS system agrees. Check all major ISPs separately — Gmail, Outlook, and Yahoo each maintain their own scores and apply different filtering rules.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why sender reputation matters for email marketing</h2>
        <p>Sender reputation is the most direct lever controlling email deliverability. Three consequences make it non-negotiable:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Inbox vs spam routing.</strong> ISPs route messages in real time based on sender score. A drop from High to Low doesn't just reduce open rates — it can halve the number of emails that ever reach recipients.</li>
          <li><strong>Cascade damage.</strong> A damaged reputation causes bounce cascades. Filtered emails generate more bounces, which further erode your score, which causes more filtering. The spiral is self-reinforcing and hard to break without drastic action.</li>
          <li><strong>Revenue impact.</strong> Email delivers $36 ROI per dollar spent when it lands in inboxes. A move from 95% to 60% inbox placement doesn't reduce revenue by 35% — it can effectively destroy the channel, since subscribers who never see your emails don't unsubscribe; they just stop engaging, which makes your score worse.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How sender reputation actually works</h2>
        <p>ISPs evaluate four primary signals, each weighted differently by provider:</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Signal</th><th>Healthy threshold</th><th>What damages it</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Bounce rate</strong></td>
                <td>Under 0.5%</td>
                <td>Sending to unvalidated or purchased lists</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Spam complaint rate</strong></td>
                <td>Below 0.1%</td>
                <td>Irrelevant content, hard-to-find unsubscribe links</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Engagement signals</strong></td>
                <td>Opens, clicks, replies</td>
                <td>Sending to inactive segments without re-engagement</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Authentication records</strong></td>
                <td>SPF + DKIM + DMARC</td>
                <td>Missing or misconfigured DNS records</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>Gmail specifically tracks whether recipients open, click, reply to, or forward your emails. High engagement signals wanted mail. Consistent deletion-without-opening tells Gmail your emails are unwanted — and it adjusts your placement accordingly, even before anyone clicks the spam button.</p>

        <h3>Authentication records explained</h3>
        <p>SPF (Sender Policy Framework) lists the mail servers authorized to send on your domain's behalf. DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail) adds a cryptographic signature that proves the message wasn't tampered with in transit. DMARC ties both together and instructs ISPs what to do when authentication fails. All three should be configured before you send your first marketing email.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Sender reputation types — domain vs IP</h2>
        <p>There are two reputation scores that matter, and they operate independently.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Domain reputation</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Tied to your sending domain (e.g., yourcompany.com)</li>
              <li>More persistent — survives IP changes</li>
              <li>Primary signal for Gmail and modern ISPs</li>
              <li>Tracked in Google Postmaster Tools</li>
              <li>Takes 4-8 weeks to establish from scratch</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>IP reputation</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Tied to the specific server IP sending your mail</li>
              <li>Shared on budget ESP platforms (shared IP)</li>
              <li>Dedicated IPs give you full control but require volume</li>
              <li>Tracked in Sender Score (0-100 scale) and SNDS</li>
              <li>Can be reset by switching IPs — but not domain reputation</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real sender reputation examples</h2>
        <p>Here are two patterns that play out repeatedly across email programs:</p>

        <h3>1. Successful warm-up from zero</h3>
        <p>A SaaS startup launched on a new domain with zero sender history. Initially, 60% of emails were blocked. They implemented a structured warm-up: starting at 50 sends per day, doubling every 3 days, sending only to their most engaged opt-ins. After six weeks at graduated volume with consistent opens above 35%, inbox placement climbed to 95%. The key was patience — any attempt to rush the warm-up at week 3 would have triggered filtering.</p>

        <h3>2. Reputation collapse from neglect</h3>
        <p>A retailer paused email marketing for four months, then blasted their full list. Without re-engagement, the 4% bounce rate and 0.4% complaint rate earned them "Bad" domain reputation in Postmaster Tools within two sends. Recovery required three months of re-warming: dropping to 200 sends per day of only recently-active subscribers, pruning 70% of the list, and fixing missing DMARC records before gradually scaling back up.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Sender reputation vs email deliverability — what's the difference</h2>
        <p>Sender reputation is one input into email deliverability. Deliverability is the outcome — the percentage of sent emails that reach the intended folder. Reputation is the biggest lever, but not the only one. Content spam triggers, blacklist status, and ISP-specific rules also affect deliverability independently of your reputation score.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices to protect sender reputation</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use double opt-in.</strong> Confirms every subscriber genuinely wants your emails, eliminating typos and bot submissions that inflate bounce rates.</li>
          <li><strong>Clean your list every 90 days.</strong> Remove hard bounces immediately. Suppress contacts who haven't opened in 6 months before reaching out with a re-engagement sequence.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up SPF, DKIM, and DMARC before sending.</strong> Authentication is table stakes. Sending without all three configured tells ISPs to be suspicious.</li>
          <li><strong>Warm up new domains and IPs gradually.</strong> Start at 50-100 sends per day, doubling every 3-5 days, using only your most engaged subscribers first.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep complaint rates below 0.1%.</strong> Make unsubscribe links visible, honor opt-out requests within 10 days, and never email people who didn't explicitly opt in.</li>
          <li><strong>Segment by engagement level.</strong> Send your most important campaigns to high-engagement segments first. Only send re-engagement sequences to dormant contacts — not your primary promotions.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor Postmaster Tools weekly.</strong> Google Postmaster Tools is free and shows your domain reputation, spam rate, and authentication status in near-real time.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a dedicated IP above 50,000 sends/month.</strong> Below that volume, a shared IP on a reputable ESP is fine. Above it, a dedicated IP ensures neighbors' behavior can't contaminate your score.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — blasting inactive lists</div>
          <p>The most common cause of reputation collapse is sending a large campaign to a list that hasn't been mailed in 4+ months. ISPs interpret the sudden engagement gap as evidence the list was purchased or the sender has lost control. Always run a re-engagement sequence on dormant contacts before any full-list send, and purge non-responders before the main campaign.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common sender reputation mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Purchasing or scraping email lists</strong> — immediate spike in bounces and complaints; can permanently damage a new domain</li>
          <li><strong>Sending without SPF/DKIM/DMARC</strong> — ISPs treat unauthenticated mail as suspicious by default</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring Google Postmaster Tools</strong> — reputation can erode for weeks before it shows in open rates</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping warm-up on new domains</strong> — even a permission-based list can trigger filtering if sent at full volume with zero history</li>
          <li><strong>Treating complaint rates as vanity metrics</strong> — 0.3% complaints is enough to trigger Gmail filtering; 0.1% is the safe ceiling</li>
          <li><strong>Rushing re-warming after a reputation drop</strong> — scaling too fast during recovery resets the damage accumulation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
